===Etymology 1===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|たち}}
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=goon|だち|k1=たち}}
From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=たち|-}}. Appears in the ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'', completed some time after 759 CE.<ref>{{RQ:Manyoshu|19|4240}}, text [https://web.archive.org/web/20211021084710/http://jti.lib.virginia.edu/japanese/manyoshu/Man19Yo.html#4240 here]</ref> The ''tachi'' reading is analyzed by some references<ref>Jim Breen's WWWJDIC, {{m|ja|達}} character entry [https://web.archive.org/web/20210808080955/http://nihongo.monash.edu/cgi-bin/wwwjdic?1MMC%E9%81%94 here]</ref> as [[訓読み#Japanese|kun'yomi]] or a native-Japanese reading. Alternatively, this has been understood as a shift from the [[呉音#Japanese|goon]] reading of ''dachi''.

Beyond Japanese, apparently related to {{cog|okm|ᄃᆞᆶ〮|tr=tólh|pos=pluralizing particle}} > {{cog|ko|-들|pos=pluralizing particle}}, perhaps reflecting Old Korean {{IPAfont|*/tatVk/}} ({{ko-ref|Vovin 2010}}, p. 120), and thus not actually of Chinese origin. However, probably phonologically reinforced by the Sino-Japanese reading of {{ncog|ltc|-}} {{ltc-l|達}}.

